of Boston's streets.\""},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"Freed Bristow days before enlisting — £60 paid","body":"On May 9, 1775 — days before leaving for war — he signed a Deed of Manumission freeing Bristow, an African man age 44, who paid £60 (roughly 400 days' wages) for his freedom. The deed reads: \"he may go & come when & wherever he pleases.\" Bristow later willed his estate to Thomas's children. A West Hartford middle school was named Bristow Middle School in 2005 — believed to be the first Connecticut school named for a formerly enslaved person."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Half-brother Roger survived — rose to Major","body":"He and his half-brother Roger Hooker — different mothers; Roger's was Anna Kellogg, his was Mercy Hart — both answered the Revolution's first call. Thomas died of disease in 1775; Roger rose to Major, carried news of Burgoyne's surrender to the British, and outlived the war by 55 years."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"His daughter Abigail married Samuel Talcott","body":"His daughter Abigail Pantry Hooker married Samuel Talcott, uniting the Hooker and Talcott founding-family lines of Hartford. This is the compiler's primary point of double descent from Thomas Hooker and the Talcott family simultaneously."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"West Hartford home now a National Register site","body":"Thomas Hart built his West Hartford home in 1770 — the Sarah Whitman Hooker Homestead at the corner of South Main Street and New Britain Avenue, where his widow Sarah continued to live and raise their children after his death. The house stands on the National Register of Historic Places, named for her."}],"documents":[{"document_id":"DOC010","document_blurb":"Summons to appear before CT General Assembly, Woodruff v. Samuel Hooker."}],"military_service":[{"war":"American Revolutionary War","rank":"Private","unit":"Suffolk County Militia, Massachusetts Militia; Connecticut volunteers from Farmington","notes":"Enlisted at first call 1775. \"One of the first to enlist.\" Joined army near Boston; died of pleurisy Nov 26, 1775 during Siege of Boston. Buried in unmarked grave at Roxbury MA.","war_id":"WAR004"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Thomas Hart Hooker","notes":"Middle name \"Hart\" commemorates his mother Mercy Hart","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Hooker","middle_name":"Hart","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"slug":"thomas-hooker-1745"},"X00253":{"id":"X00253","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1747,"month":2,"day":27,"city":"West Hartford","county":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1837,"month":6,"day":5,"city":"West Hartford","county":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"gender":"female","parents":{},"number_of_marriages":2,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00303","date_year":1769,"date_month":2,"date_day":1,"location_city":"Farmington","location_county":"Hartford","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1775,"children_ids":["H00687","H00688"]},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"X00254","date_year":1779,"date_month":4,"date_day":8,"location_city":"West Hartford","location_county":"Hartford","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1793,"children_ids":[]}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"baptism":{"year":1747,"month":3,"day":1,"city":"West Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Her grandfather succeeded Rev. Samuel Hooker at Farmington","body":"Her grandfather Rev. Samuel Whitman succeeded Rev. Samuel Hooker as minister at Farmington — making her family already entwined with the Hooker line before her marriage. Rev. Samuel Whitman's mother Anna Alcock was a granddaughter of Rev. Thomas Hooker's sister."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Widowed in 1775 — remarried four years later","body":"Her first husband Thomas Hart Hooker died of pleurisy during the Siege of Boston on November 26, 1775. On April 8, 1779 she married Capt. Seth Collins of West Hartford as his second wife. She died at West Hartford on June 5, 1837."}],"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM005","landmark_blurb":"She lived here with first husband Thomas Hart Hooker, then with second husband Capt. Seth Collins."}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Whitman Collins","first_name":"Sarah","last_name":"Collins","maiden_name":"Whitman","married_names":["Hooker","Collins"]},"residence":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"sarah-whitman-1747"},"H00687":{"id":"H00687","visible_default":true,"in_talcott_book":true,"has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"generation_from_john_talcott":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"compiler_ancestor":true,"lineage_note":"Thomas¹ → Samuel²(H00007) → John³ → Roger⁴ → Thomas⁵ → Abigail⁶ Pantry Hooker","intersection_note":"Descends from Thomas Hooker (paternal) AND marries into Talcott line (T01389). Compiler descends from her through Talcott line.","is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1770,"month":1,"day":23,"city":"West Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1854,"month":3,"day":16,"city":"West Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United 